Vladimir Putin and the Risk of World War III
San Francisco – Russia’s invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of what could destroy our civilization in a Third World War.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had held a long meeting on February 4 – that day was the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
Following the meeting, the two released a carefully crafted, 5,000-word document declaring the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is more powerful than any treaty and surely required meticulous negotiations beforehand.
I am stunned that Xi seems to have fully entrusted Putin with launching the invasion and war in Ukraine.
He believes that confirming himself as a lifelong ruler of China this year is merely a formality, and he is confident about it.
After consolidating all power in his hands, Xi meticulously planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's backing, Putin set out to achieve his own lifelong dream in an unimaginably brutal manner.
At 70, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it is either now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that Russian citizens need a tsar to blindly follow.
This system is the complete opposite of democratic societies, and this vision distorts the "souls" of emotionally and sentimentally overwhelmed Russian citizens.
In my childhood, I had many interactions with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they would share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I called my political charity work.
Initially, I established a foundation in my home country, Hungary, and then became actively involved in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
The breakup had already begun when Mikhail Gorbachev took office in 1985.
I also set up foundations in Russia, and subsequently in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation here (I closed my foundation in 1989, shortly before the crackdown in Tiananmen Square).
I do not personally know Putin, but I have been closely following his rise to power and fully understand his cold and ruthless nature.
He reduced the Chechen capital Grozny to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Ukraine’s capital, Kyiv.
Putin was a shrewd KGB agent, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality as he has developed a fixed mindset.
There's no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but it turned out they were no different from Ukrainian speakers.
Despite the apparent one-sidedness, Ukrainian civilians still demonstrated an incredible heroic resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article claiming that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one people, and that Ukrainians were misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Given that Kiev was the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, his argument's first part does have historical basis.
But in the content of Part 2, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have known the facts much better.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests that broke out in 2014.
The events of 2014 made him very angry.
But when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
Defence Ministry awards contracts still deeply entrenched corruption played a significant role in this poor performance.
But instead of blaming himself, Putin seems to have lost his mind.
He is determined to punish Ukraine for its opposition, and his actions appear to be unbridled.
He has thrown the entire Russian army into battle and disregarded all rules of engagement, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals have been attacked, and the power grid supplying electricity to the Chernobyl nuclear plant (now occupied by Russian troops) has also been destroyed.
In the encircled Mariupol, over 400,000 people have gone without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The US and EU are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine while also trying to buy MiG fighters that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate, Russian-made MiGs.
This could change the whole situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has already achieved a miracle in strengthening Europe's resolve and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin had strayed.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remained "as solid as ever," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to be as restrained as possible during the war.
It remains to be seen whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that before they destroy our civilization, Putin and Xi will be removed from power.
